The Smart Hospital Emergency Triage System is a Java-based application designed to simulate how hospitals prioritize patients in emergency situations. 
The system focuses on analyzing patient conditions and dynamically deciding which patient should receive treatment first.
In real-world hospitals, not all patients are treated on a first-come, first-served basis. 
Instead, patients are prioritized based on the severity of their condition, urgency, and other factors. 
This project replicates that logic using Object-Oriented Programming principles.
The system allows users to add patients by providing basic information such as name, severity level, age, and patient type (Normal, Critical, or VIP). 
Based on these inputs, each patient is assigned a priority score. Critical patients receive the highest priority, followed by VIP patients, and then normal patients.
The application then sorts patients dynamically according to their priority and identifies which patient should be treated first. 
It also categorizes patients into emergency levels such as RED (Critical), YELLOW (Moderate), and GREEN (Low) for better visualization of urgency.
This project effectively demonstrates the four core pillars of Object-Oriented Programming:
Encapsulation is used to protect patient data by keeping attributes private and accessing them through getter methods.
Abstraction is achieved through the use of an abstract Patient class, which defines the structure for all patient types.
Inheritance allows different types of patients (Normal, Critical, VIP) to derive from the base class.
Polymorphism is implemented by overriding the getPriority() method, enabling different behaviors for different patient types.
Overall, this system is a simple yet powerful simulation of real-world hospital triage, combining human decision-making logic with programming concepts 
to create an intelligent and dynamic solution.
